Looking at all the scatter and box plots it shows the signs of non-linearity and non constant variance. Also, it helps to take the log of Wages.

Lets create a bwplot to see if there is any interaction between variables.

wages_df$logwage = log(wages_df$Wage)

library(lattice)
bwplot(logwage~Region | Black, data = wages_df)

Looking at the bwplot, the plots are very similar to each other and hence doesnt show any interactions between the varaibles. Lets confirm this by a nested F test.

Lets create 2 linear models one without the interactions and other with the interactions and then perform nested F test.

regwage = lm(logwage ~ Education + Experience + as.factor(Black) + as.factor(SMSA) + as.factor(Region) , data= wages_df)

Lets perform the nested F test:

anova(regwage_interaction,regwage )
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: logwage ~ Education + Experience + as.factor(Black) + as.factor(SMSA) + 
##     as.factor(Region) + as.factor(Region) * as.factor(Black)
## Model 2: logwage ~ Education + Experience + as.factor(Black) + as.factor(SMSA) + 
##     as.factor(Region)
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq     F Pr(>F)
## 1  25620 7234.7                          
## 2  25623 7235.1 -3  -0.35328 0.417 0.7408

We can see that the F statiscs is 0.417 and p value is 0.7408. The p value suggest that the interactions are not statsically significant and des not add value to this model.

Experience_square = wages_df$Experience^2

regwage_final = lm(logwage ~ Education + Experience + Experience_square + as.factor(Black) + as.factor(SMSA) + as.factor(Region), data= wages_df)


summary(regwage_final)

The confidence interval of the variables are:

exp(confint(regwage_final))
##                          2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept)         79.3354934 85.580526
## Education            1.0898389  1.094862
## Experience           1.0560268  1.059712
## Experience_square    0.9991027  0.999178
## as.factor(Black)Yes  0.7731625  0.811006
## as.factor(SMSA)Yes   1.1612718  1.195580
## as.factor(Region)NE  1.0255781  1.063884
## as.factor(Region)S   0.9234603  0.955630
## as.factor(Region)W   0.9706303  1.007459

This means that 95% times the model captures the true value of the variable.

Interpretation:

Black: Keeping other values constant, if the person is black then the mutliplicative factor associated with the median of wages changes by 0.7918368. CI is between 0.7731625 and 0.811006

Education: Keep the other value constant, if the Education changes by 1 unit then the multiplicative factor accociated with median of wages changes by 1.092349. CI is between 1.0898389 and 1.094862

SMSA: Keeping the other values constant, if the its a metro then the multiplicative factor associated with the median of the wage changes by 1.178332. CI is between 1.1612718 and 1.195580

Region: Keeping the other values constant, if the Region is NE then the multiplicative factor associated with the median of the wage chnages by 1.044554. CI is between 1.0255781 and 1.063884

Keeping the other values constant, if the Region is S then the multiplicative factor associated with the median of the wage chnages by 0.9394037. CI is between 0.9234603 and 0.955630.

Keeping the other values constant, if the Region is W then the multiplicative factor associated with the median of the wage chnages by 0.9888724. CI is between 0.9706303 and 1.007459.

Experience: We can understand the effect of experience on speed by plotting a graph:

plot(y = regwage_final$fitted.values, x = wages_df$Experience, xlab ="Experience", ylab = "Fitted values")

Plot the residuals against all the independnt variables and fitted values.

plot(regwage_final$residuals, x= wages_df$Education, ylab = "Residuals")
abline(0,0)

plot(regwage_final$residuals, x= wages_df$Experience, ylab = "Residuals")
abline(0,0)

plot(regwage_final$residuals, x= regwage_final$fitted.values, ylab = "Residuals")
abline(0,0)

boxplot(regwage_final$residuals~wages_df$Black, ylab = "Residuals")

boxplot(regwage_final$residuals~wages_df$SMSA, ylab = "Residuals")

boxplot(regwage_final$residuals~wages_df$Region, ylab = "Residuals")

qqnorm(regwage_final$residuals, ylab = "Residuals", main = "Normal quantile plot of residuals")

Based on the residual plots and box plot we can see that residual does not exhibit constant variance.

The qq plot shows that some points are not on the line and hence does not completely statisfy normal distribution.

Limitation: The r_sqaured value is really low for the model. It is somewhat difficult to explain the model as we are using experience square (quadratic function) The residual does not show constant variance. The rediusal does not follow a perfect normal distribution.
